com.parse4cn1

Class ParsePush

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.parse4cn1.ParsePush

  • public class ParsePush
extends java.lang.Object
    The ParsePush is a local representation of data that can be sent as a push notification.

    The typical workflow for sending a push notification from the client is to construct a new ParsePush, use the setter functions to fill it with data, and then use ParsePush.send() to send it.

    Notes:
    1. In order to use send push notifications, Client Push should be enabled in the Parse App settings. Bear in mind, however, that it is recommended not to enable client push in production apps.
    2. Unlike the corresponding ParsePush class from the Parse Android SDK, methods for channel subscription and unsubscription are available in this library via the ParseInstallation where they arguably more naturally belong.

    • Method Detail

      • create

        public static ParsePush create()
        Creates a new push notification.

        The default channel is the empty string, also known as the global broadcast channel, but this value can be overridden using setChannel(java.lang.String), setChannels(java.util.Collection) or setQuery(com.parse4cn1.ParseQuery). Before sending the push notification you must call either setMessage(java.lang.String) or #setData(org.json.JSONObject).

        Returns:
        The newly created Push notification.

      • isAppOpenedViaPushNotification

        public static boolean isAppOpenedViaPushNotification()
        Checks whether the app is being opened via a push notification, e.g., by clicking the notification in the 'status bar'.

        This call will return false if the app was in the foreground when it received the app opened push payload because in that case, the payload would be consumed directly by invoking ParsePush.IPushCallback.onAppOpenedViaPush(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject).

        Note that the result returned by this method is guaranteed to be correct if the app is correctly managing the data, i.e., checking every time the app is opened (typically in the start() method of the app's main class) and resetting the data after processing.

        Returns:
        true if app open push data is found; otherwise returns false.

      • isUnprocessedPushDataAvailable

        public static boolean isUnprocessedPushDataAvailable()
        Checks whether there is pending unprocessed push data.

        Generally, this is data from push notifications that the app did not handle but could not be scheduled as status bar notifications. A good example is a hidden push message which has no 'alert' or 'title' data and is thus never shown scheduled as a status bar notification. However, like everything else with native Push, the actual semantics are dependent on the native implementation which may vary from app to app.

        Note that the response returned by this method is guaranteed to be correct if and only if the app is correctly managing the data, i.e., checking every time the app is opened (typically in the start() method of the app's main class) and resetting the data after processing.

        Returns:
        true if unprocessed push data is found; otherwise returns false.

      • getPushDataUsedToOpenApp

        public static ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject getPushDataUsedToOpenApp()
                                                                     throws ParseException
        Retrieves app open push data, if present.

        This data must be set by the native push implementations via handlePushOpen(java.lang.String, boolean).

        This call will return null if the app was in the foreground when it received the app opened push payload because in that case, the payload would be consumed directly by invoking ParsePush.IPushCallback.onAppOpenedViaPush(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject).

        Note that the result returned by this method is guaranteed to be correct if and only if the app is correctly managing the data, i.e., checking every time the app is opened (typically in the start() method of the app's main class) and resetting the data after processing.

        Returns:
        The app open push data or null if none is found
        Throws:
        ParseException - If anything goes wrong with parsing the JSON data.
        See Also:
        resetPushDataUsedToOpenApp()

      • getUnprocessedPushData

        public static ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONArray getUnprocessedPushData()
                                                                  throws ParseException
        Retrieves unprocessed push data, if present.

        This data must be set by the native push implementations via handleUnprocessedPushReceived(java.lang.String).

        Note that the result returned by this method is guaranteed to be correct if and only if the app is correctly managing the data, i.e., checking every time the app is opened (typically in the start() method of the app's main class) and resetting the data after processing.

        Returns:
        The pending push data in the same order as they were received or null if none is found.
        Throws:
        ParseException - If anything goes wrong with parsing the JSON data.
        See Also:
        resetUnprocessedPushData()

      • setPushCallback

        public static void setPushCallback(ParsePush.IPushCallback callback)
        Sets the push callback.

        This call removes any previously set callback since there can be at most one callback per app.

        If there's a push registration failure notification from the native code, ParsePush.IPushCallback.onPushRegistrationFailed(com.parse4cn1.ParseException) will be invoked immediately.

        Parameters:
        callback - The Push callback to be set or null to remove the current callback.

      • handlePushReceivedForeground

        public static boolean handlePushReceivedForeground(java.lang.String jsonPushPayload)
        This method should be called by the native push implementation when a push message is received and the app is judged to be in the foreground (as must be determined in native code).

        The provided data is forward to the push callback if any by calling ParsePush.IPushCallback.onPushReceivedForeground(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject).

        Parameters:
        jsonPushPayload - The push data.
        Returns:
        true if the app has processed the push message and no further scheduling is needed; otherwise returns false.

      • handlePushReceivedBackground

        public static boolean handlePushReceivedBackground(java.lang.String jsonPushPayload)
        This method should be called by the native push implementation when a push message is received and the app is judged to be running but not in the foreground (as must be determined in native code).

        The provided data is forward to the push callback if any by calling ParsePush.IPushCallback.onPushReceivedBackground(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject).

        Parameters:
        jsonPushPayload - The push data.
        Returns:
        true if the app has processed the push message and no further scheduling is needed; otherwise returns false.

      • handleUnprocessedPushReceived

        public static void handleUnprocessedPushReceived(java.lang.String jsonPushPayload)
        This method should be called by the native push implementation whenever there is a push message that was not scheduled for 'status bar' notification, e.g. so-called 'hidden' push message. It is up to the native implementation to decide what is hidden.

        The provided data is added in FIFO order to the collection of unprocessed push messages. The app can retrieve this data by calling getUnprocessedPushData() after optionally establishing availability via isUnprocessedPushDataAvailable().

        Parameters:
        jsonPushPayload - The push data.

      • handlePushOpen

        public static void handlePushOpen(java.lang.String jsonPushPayload,
                                  boolean isAppInForeground)
        This method should be called by the native push implementation whenever the app is about to be opened as a result of clicking a 'status bar' notification.

        If the app is already running and in the foreground, i.e., isAppInForeground=true, the push data will directly be deliver to the app via ParsePush.IPushCallback.onAppOpenedViaPush(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject) or simply ignored if there's no callback set. Conversely, if the app is not yet running , i.e., isAppInForeground=false, the data will be stored until the app requests for it via getPushDataUsedToOpenApp() possibly after first checking for availability via isAppOpenedViaPushNotification().

        Parameters:
        jsonPushPayload - The push data.
        isAppInForeground - The foreground status of the app that determines when and how jsonPushPayload is made available to the app.

      • handlePushRegistrationStatus

        public static void handlePushRegistrationStatus(java.lang.String error,
                                                int type)
        This method should be called by the native push implementation to report the push notification registration status.
        Parameters:
        error - A description of what went wrong or null if registration was successful.
        type - A parameter to distinguish the kind of problem. The values currently supported are:
        0 - Registration succeeded
        1 - Generic failure
        2 - Failure due to missing parameters or configuration
        3 - Error while saving/updating installation to backend

      • setChannel

        public void setChannel(java.lang.String channel)
        Sets the channel on which this push notification will be sent.

        A push can either have channels or a query so setting this will unset the query.

        Note that only devices subscribed to this channel will receive the push notification. Subscription to channels is handled via the ParseInstallation class.

        Parameters:
        channel - The channel to be set. Replaces any previously set channel(s).

      • setChannels

        public void setChannels(java.util.Collection<java.lang.String> channels)
        Sets the collection of channels on which this push notification will be sent.

        A push can either have channels or a query so setting this will unset the query.

        Note that only devices subscribed to at least one of these channel will receive the push notification. Subscription to channels is handled via the ParseInstallation class.

        Parameters:
        channels - The channels to be set (possibly null). Replace any previously set channels.

      • setExpirationTime

        public void setExpirationTime(java.util.Date time)
        Sets a UNIX epoch timestamp at which this notification should expire, in seconds (UTC).

        A push can either have an expiration time or an expiration time interval so calling this method overrules any previously set (java.util.Date) expiration time interval.

        Parameters:
        time - The expiration time of this push message in seconds (UTC).

      • setExpirationTimeInterval

        A push can either have an expiration time or an expiration time interval so calling this method overrules any previously set expiration time.

        Parameters:
        timeInterval - The expiration time interval in seconds.

      • setData

        public void setData(ca.weblite.codename1.json.JSONObject data)
        Sets the entire data of the push message. This is useful for sending custom messages with 'raw' JSON payloads.

        Note that calling this method replaces any data that was previously set. Use setData(java.lang.String, java.lang.String) instead to add/modify a specific field in the payload.

      • setQuery

        public void setQuery(ParseQuery<ParseInstallation> query)
        Sets the query for this push for which this push notification will be sent.

        This query will be executed in the Parse cloud; this push notification will be sent to Installations which this query yields. A push can either have channels or a query. Setting this will unset the channels.

        Parameters:
        query - A query to which this push should target. This must be a ParseInstallation query.

      • send

        public void send()
          throws ParseException
        Sends this push notification while blocking this thread until the push notification has successfully reached the Parse servers.

        Note that the messages are sent via cloud code since sending of of push messages requires the Master key which is not exposed via parse4cn1. As such a 'sendPushViaRestApi' cloud code function must be defined in the Parse backend taking the following parameters:

         - server: The Parse server URL without trailing backslash.
 - payload: The HTTP POST request payload conforming the the REST API for sending Parse push notifications.
        Such a function is already present in the same cloud code delivered along with parse4cn1 (see https://github.com/sidiabale/parse4cn1/tree/master/cloud)
        Throws:
        ParseException - if anything goes wrong.
